<html><TITLE>Top Ten Facts -- Heritage</TITLE><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg"><center><img src="/heritage/thf_log2.gif"></a><h2>The <i>Right</i> Numbers</h2>Compiled from the 1990 Long Form Census information<p><h3>Top Ten Facts for Week of April 22, 1996</h3></center><p><hr><p>
1.  Percentage of minimum wage earners that are the <b>sole breadwinners</b> in their families: 
<p><center>
<b>23%</b>
</center>
<p><hr><p>
2. Percentage of minimum wage earners that are <b>full-year, full-time employees</b>: <p><center>
<b>16%</b>
</center><p>
<hr><P>

3.  Percent of <b>23.5 million working poor families</b> working at <b>minimum wage</b>: 
<p><center><b>2%</b></center>
<p>
<hr><p>
4. Percent of minimum wage earners under 21: <p>
<center><b>about 50%</b></center>
<p>
Their average family income:<p>
<center><b> $47,000</b></center>

<p>
Source: Wilson, Mark, "Why Raising the Minimum Wage is a Bad Idea," Heritage Foundation <I>Backgrounder</I>  No. 1033, May 17, 1995.; March 1994 CPS.
<p><hr><p>
5.  Percentage of minimum wage earners that will be earning <b>20 percent more than minimum wage within 12 months</b>:
<p><center><b> 63%</b></center>
<p>
Source: Ralph E. Smith and Bruce Vavrichek, "The Wage Mobility of Minimum Wage Workers," <I>Industrial Relations and Labor Review</I>, Vol. XLVI, No. 1 (October 1992), pp. 82-88. 
<p><hr><P>

6.  Average duration of  <b>"poverty spells"</b> for those with <b>no work disability</b>, according to the Census Bureau: 
<P><center><b>7 months</b></center>
<p><hr><p>
7. Where the <b>Bottom Quintile in 1975</b> ended up by <b>1991</b>:
<br> The first quintile represents the bottom 1/5 of income earners, the 5th quintile the top 1/5 of income earners:
<P><center><table border cellpadding="5">
<tr>
<th>1991 Quintiles</th><td>1st</td><td>2nd</td><td>3rd</td><td>4th</td><td>5th</td>
</tr><tr>
<th>1975 Bottom Quintile</th><td>5.1%</td><td>14.6%</td><td>21.0%</td><td>30.3%</td><td>29.0%</td>
</tr></table>












</center><p>
Source: University of Michigan's Panel Survey on Income Dynamics
<p><hr><p>

8. Increase of <b>Average Annual Expenditures per consumer unit</b>:
<p><center><table border cellpadding="5">
<tr>
<th>Year</th><th>Increase</th></tr>
<tr><td>1991</td><td>4%</td></tr>
<tr><td>1992</td><td>1%</td></tr>
<tr><td>1993</td><td>3%</td></tr>








</table></center><p>
Source: Bureau of Labor Statistics data
<p><hr><P>
9. Women in the <b>1980's</b> had <b>55% higher real earnings over women in the 1970's</b> in every age, income and education category.
<p>
Source: National Commission for Employment Policy, "On Shaky Ground:  Rising Fears about Incomes and Earnings"
<p><hr><p>
10.  <b>Median  Age</b> of the United States Population:<br>
(with projections)
<p><center><table border cellpadding="5">
<th><br></th><td>1995</td><td>2015</td><td>2030</td></tr>
<th>Median Age</th><td>33</td><td>37</td><td>39</td></tr>
</table></center><p>

<I>Economic Report of the President</I>, February 1996
