<head>
<title>Phil Gram Biography</title>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Phil Gramm Biography</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<br>
PHIL GRAMM, of College Station, Texas, is 52 years old. He holds a Ph.D. in
economics, the subject he taught for 12 years at Texas A&M University.<p>
Senator Gramm won election to Congress as a Democrat in 1978, and he was
re-elected in 1980 and 1982. In 1983, when the Democratic leadership
stripped Phil of his House Budget Committee seat in retaliation for
co-authoring the Reagan economic program, he resigned from Congress, went
back to Texas, and won re-election as a Republican on Lincoln's birthday,
back to Texas, and won re-election as a Republican on Lincoln's birthday,
February 12, 1983. In 1984 he ran successfully for the United States Senate,
 winning more votes than any candidate for statewideoffice had ever received
 in the history of Texas. In 1990, Phil was re-elected with the highest percentage 
vote received by any Senatecandidate in a general election in over 30 years.<p>
Phil Gramm wrote three pieces of landmark economic legislation-the
Gramm-Latta Budget, the Gramm-Latta Reconciliation Act and the Gramm-Rudman
balanced budget bill. He also distinguished himself by leading the effort
to defeat the Clinton Health Care Plan.<p>
The Gramm-Latta budgets reduced federal spending, strengthened national
defense, mandated the 1981 tax cut and implemented President Reagan's
economic program. Gramm-Rudman was the only real deficit reduction effort
in the last twenty years. From 1985 until Congress repealed it in 1990,
Gramm-Rudman cut the deficit by 40 percent and reduced the size of
government relative to the size of the economy by 10 percent.<p>
As Chairman of the National Republican Senatorial Committee, Phil Gramm led
the successful effort to win a Republican majority in the U.S. Senate in
the 1994 elections.<p>
He authored several books and numerous articles in economics prior to being
elected to Congress.<p>
Phil is married to Dr. Wendy Lee Gramm, former Chairman of the Commodity
Futures Trading Commission, and they have two college aged sons, Marshall
and Jeff. The Gramms are Episcopalians.<p>
<br>
<a href="http://www.gramm96.org">Go to Phil Gramm Home Page</a><br>
<a href="gramspee.html">Go to Phil Gramm's <STRONG>American Dream</STRONG> Speech</a><br>
<a href="contents.html">Introduction</a>
</body>
</html>

              
