<html>
<head>
<title>Pete Wilson: Biography</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Pete Wilson: Biography</h2>
</center>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
As Governor of California since 1991, Pete Wilson has not only led his state through tough times, but has achieved fundamental change that has attracted attention from around the nation.
<P>
Throughout his career, Pete Wilson has shown the optimism, confidence,
vision, and courage to make change and to lead.
<P>
Governor Wilson has enacted what <I>The San Francisco Chronicle</I> called "some of the boldest welfare reforms in the nation" to promote work and encourage individual responsibility."
<P>
He was the first governor in the nation to sign a "Three Strikes and You're Out" bill into law. He also sponsored and signed California's "One Strike" law, one of the toughest laws in the country targeting rapists and child molesters.  And Pete Wilson was
 the first governor in a quarter-century to enforce California's death penalty.
<P>
Governor Wilson is the national leader in the drive to stop illegal immigration. He was a leading proponent in the successful campaign to pass Proposition 187, an initiative to cut off taxpayer-supported services to illegal immigrants.
<P>
Pete Wilson has achieved all this despite a first term that saw natural disasters -- including floods, earthquakes and wildfires -- a prolonged recession, severe cutbacks in California's aerospace industry and painful military base closings.
<P>
But then, Pete Wilson has never shied away from a challenge.
<P>
Pete Wilson has born August 23, 1933, in Lake Forest, Illinois, and raised in Missouri, where he excelled as a student and an athlete. He attended Yale University on a Naval ROTC scholarship and served three years as a Marine Corps infantry officer before

going on to earn a law degree from the University of California, Berkeley.
<P>
Elected to the California Assembly in 1966, the same year that Ronald Reagan was first elected governor, Pete Wilson went on to serve as the highly effective Mayor of San Diego for more than a decade. He amended the city charter to make public safety the 
first and most important responsibility of city government and increased the number of
police officers patrolling San Diego's streets.
<P>
As a United States Senator, Pete Wilson's fiscal conservatism earned him the Watchdog of the Treasury Award every year when he was in Washington. And his toughness was proven yet again when, recovering from a burst appendix, he was wheeled into the Senate
 on a gurney to cast a tie-breaking vote for deficit reduction.
<P>
As Governor of California, Governor Wilson has made the tough choices necessary to keep state spending  $18 billion below the level projected four years earlier and to actually reduce the state's General Fund budget from one year to the next, for the firs
t time since World War II.  He also trimmed the state bureaucracy to its lowest level, as a percentage of state population, since Ronald Reagan was governor.
<P>
To improve California's jobs climate, Governor Wilson reformed the state's notoriously corrupt and job-killing workers' compensation system -- reforms that have cut rates by more than 30 percent.  He enacted job-creating tax incentives equal to a 10 perce
nt cut in the corporate and business income tax, and is now pursuing a 15 percent tax cut for every business and individual in the state.
<P>
In 1994, Governor Wilson was overwhelmingly re-elected by the voters, who gave him more votes than any other governor in California history.  
<P>
During his re-election campaign, <I>The Los Angeles Times</I> broke a 24-year tradition of neutrality in gubernatorial races to endorse Governor Wilson for re-election saying: "Wilson is a firm, hands-on administrator ... [who] is taking on the state
bureaucracy and streamlining government."
<P>
<I>The San Francisco Chronicle</I> also endorsed him noting that "Wilson's effectiveness, industry, persistence and toughness under fire have been tested and proven in the cauldron of a painful and gloomy period of California history."
<P>
In his second Inaugural Address, Governor Wilson described his vision for a better California as a place "where work is respected and rewarded, where every right is balanced by responsibility, and where freedom thrives and opportunity burns bright."
<P>
The Governor lives in suburban Sacramento with his wife, Gayle, and enjoys reading history and cheering for the San Diego Chargers.
<br>
<a href="http://www.sjmercury.com/wilson.htm">Go to the Pete Wilson Unnoficial Home Page</a><br>
<a href="wilspee.html">Pete Wilson discusses Affirmative Action</a><br>
<a href="contents.html">Introduction</a>
</body>
