<head>
<title>Alan Keyes Biography</title>
</head>
<center>
<h2>Alan Keyes Biography</h2>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<b>Public Servant</b><br>
<ul>
<li>Twice Nominated for the United States Senate in Maryland
<li>First African American of note to be a subject of an exploratory committee for the Republican presidential nomination for 1996
</ul><br>
<b>Diplomat</b><p>
<ul>
<li>Ambassador to the U.N. Economic and Social Council
<li>Assistant Secretary of State for International Organizations
</ul><br>
<b>Writer, Public Speaker, and Media Personality</b><p>
<ul>
<li>Columnist, with a weekly nationally distributed column on current affairs
<li>Author of <i>MASTERS OF THE DREAM: The Strength and Betrayal of Black America</i>, a book from William Morrow, Co.
<li>Speaker and Lecturer on a wide range of national and foreign policy issues
<li>Host of <i>The Alan Keyes Show: America's Wake-Up Call</i>, a nationally-syndicated call-in radio talk show
<li>A nationally known and respected commentator, Keyes has appeared on:<br>
<ul>
<li>ABC's Nightline
<li>NBC's Today Show
<li>CBS' Morning News
<li>PBS' MacNeil-Lehrer
<li>CNN's Crossfire
<li>CNN's Larry King Live
</ul>
<li>Keyes featured prominently in the PBS' Specials:
<ul>
<li>"Days of Rage" (1989)
<li>"Black American Conservatism" (1991)
<li>"The Issue is Race" (1992)
</ul>
</ul><br>
<b>Citizen Activist</b><p>
<ul>
<li>President of Citizens Against Government Waste (CAGW)
<li>Founder of CAGW's National Taxpayer's Action Day
</ul><br>
<b>Educator</b><p>
<ul>
<li>Interim President of Alabama A&M University
</ul><br>
<b>Personal</b><p>
<ul>
<li>Ph.D. in Government from Harvard University
<li>Married to Jocelyn, three children, ages 6, 9 and 12
</ul><P>
<br>
