<html>
<head>
<title>SC Education Foundation</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<i>November 1994</i>
<hr>
<br>
<i>South Carolina Policy Council Education Foundation<br> 
Issue Paper: Analyzing South Carolina Public Policy</i><p>
<h2>CAN THE MARKETPLACE SAVE OUR SCHOOLS?</h2> 
<i><b>By James R. Rinehart and Jackson F. Lee, Jr.</b></i><p> 
</center>
<hr>
<br> 
Problems continue to mount in our public schools. Should we give 
private schools more of a chance?<p> 
 Sometimes it's hard not to feel smug. The current struggle to 
move from central planning to a free market approach within the 
former Soviet Union and its neighboring countries has led some 
Americans to get that "we told you so" feeling. It's not that we 
revel in the misery and uncertainty faced by the residents of 
these countries, but many of us have known all along of the 
incredible deficiencies in central planning and the enormous 
power embodied in free markets. We have no problem understanding 
that the collapsing economies of Eastern Europe owe their failure 
to government ownership and control. <p>
Surprisingly, the lessons that are still being learned at such a 
high cost to the Eastern Europeans seem to be lost on most 
Americans. We continue to call for, and support government 
solutions to problems that would be solved better through private 
enterprise. Somehow, we just don't get it. Either we fail to 
recognize the costs associated with government involvement in the 
production and distribution of goods and services, or we know 
what is happening but feel unable or unwilling to do anything 
about it. The answer is probably both. Year after year, the 
influence of American government on the lives of Americans 
continues to grow. A telling measure of that growth is government 
spending as a percentage of GNP, which has tripled since 1929. <p>
We take it for granted that in the United States, the very cradle 
of free enterprise, governments should own and operate such wide 
ranging enterprises as parks, roads, postal services, buses, 
trains, hospitals, airports, sewer and water systems, garbage 
disposal services, jails, fire departments, and schools. We are 
even willing to tolerate the ever expanding regulation of 
thousands of private firms and individuals. At the state level 
alone, we license and control more than 4,000 occupations and 
professions. <p>
As we watch the centrally planned economies around the world 
disappear and move toward privatization, we see little real 
progress toward lessening the reach of government here at home. 
Some favorable signs, however, are appearing on the horizon. Many 
local and state governments are divesting themselves of 
activities that used to fall almost exclusively within the domain 
of the state. Private companies are beginning to take over such 
diverse services as prisons, garages, refuse collection 
facilities, transit systems, fire departments, waste disposal 
units, ambulance services, and low-cost housing. The driving 
Economic Report of the President, U.S. Superintendent of 
Documents, force behind these efforts is the U.S. Government 
Printing Office, Washington D C (various years) growing 
realization that privatization is more efficient and provides 
better quality service. <p>
<center><h3>WHY GOVERNMENT CONTROL DOESN'T WORK </center></h3><p>
The current interest in educational vouchers and choice 
represents the application of privatization in the area of 
education. Choice involving private schools shows real promise 
for educational reform. Of the many critics making vitriolic 
complaints about the quality of American public schools, most 
fail to see that government monopolization of education is a 
significant contributor to these poor results. A brief look at 
the government's involvement in education illustrates just how 
desperately we need to privatize our schools. <p>
Although local government schools go back to colonial times, 
until the mid-19th century, the general thrust was toward private 
schools. The transformation to our current system began when 
Horace Mann became Secretary of the newly created Board of 
Education in Massachusetts in 1837. He immediately started 
Massachusetts and this nation on a course that resulted in 
centralized, state controlled, and government owned public 
schools financed by property taxes. The net effect of universal 
free education supported by compulsory taxes and compulsory 
attendance laws was to entice, and sometimes force, parents to 
send their children to public schools. It also led many parents 
to forfeit control over their children's education under the 
mistaken assumption that responsibility lies with the schools. 
Today, fewer than 12 percent of American elementary and secondary 
students attend private schools. <p>
Everyone more or less agrees that public schools are failing 
miserably to reach even the most modest expectations set for 
them. The massive but largely ineffective school reform movement 
of the 1980s is a manifestation of this fact. What is not so well 
recognized is that public schools are failing largely because of 
the government's involvement in the production of education -- 
precisely the same phenomenon that has caused the collapse of the 
economies of many Eastern European countries. <p>
We are well aware of the fact that changing social conditions 
caused by weakened families, increased crime, and drugs have 
adverse effects on the educational achievement of children, but 
schools must adjust to educate students in any environment, and 
government schools find it almost impossible to do that. 
Government must perform a few functions, but managing the 
education of more than 40 million youngsters is just not one of 
them. <p>
The absence of effective incentives on the part of those who 
consume and those who produce education explains the poor results 
we get. The consumers of education, the students and parents, 
have little power to influence what educators do. This feeling of 
powerlessness often results in apathy and neglect. The producers 
of education, on the other hand, have few direct incentives to 
satisfy students and parents. Educators are not consistently or 
tangibly rewarded or penalized on the basis of how well their 
students learn. Instead, they are rewarded on the basis of the 
number of degrees held, and years of teaching experience. Neither 
of these factors correlates very well with student achievement or 
satisfaction. <p>
Educational decisions are largely political, and rest primarily 
in the hands of the state and local departments of education. 
Everyone from members of boards of education and superintendents 
to principals and teachers try to satisfy their superiors. 
Although educational leaders are often aware of community 
demands, nowhere are they forced to be responsive to the wishes 
of their student and parent clients. Educators actively try to 
influence school board members and state and local politicians 
because these people have the power to provide pay raises, job 
security, and better working conditions. Politicians, in turn, 
appeal to voters and special interest groups in an attempt to get 
reelected. Students and parents find themselves at the bottom of 
the hierarchy with little influence and even less clout. <p>
<center><h3>WHY FREE COMPETITIVE MARKETS DO WORK </center></h3><p>
The marketplace comes to terms with how to meet customer demands. 
Free competitive markets exhibit a power hierarchy significantly 
different from that seen in the public school system. The 
emphasis, from the owner of a company to the lowest paid 
employee, is on customer satisfaction, because everyone realizes 
that the customer always has the option of taking his or her 
business elsewhere. Failure to retain and satisfy customers leads 
to losses. Success in retaining and satisfying customers 
generates profits. The incentive system gives central importance 
to the customer. <p>
No similar incentive operates within the public school system. 
Rewards for educators, such as they are, follow regardless of 
student achievement. Salaries are based almost exclusively on 
degrees held and years of experience. Rewards can even come as a 
direct result of poor quality. Educators often argue that poor 
results are due to inadequate funding, so, the weaker the 
results, the greater the financial need. It is an interesting 
fact that we heap accolades on schools with high per capita 
spending while deprecating those with low spending per capita. 
Imagine a private firm such as IBM complaining because their cost 
of making computers is too low! <p>
If we really want to improve education, we need to rediscover the 
power of unregulated markets. At a minimum, we should provide 
parents with credit vouchers so they can choose between public 
and private school alternatives. But an even better solution can 
be found in the privatization of the entire educational system. <p>
Under privatization, state and local governments could sell their 
school properties. Parents could be given a coupon equal to the 
average amount currently spent on education. The coupon could 
then be used to pay tuition at any school (all would be private) 
selected. Competition among schools would keep tuition levels 
under control and force them to satisfy the wishes of students 
and parents. Schools that successfully satisfied their consumers 
would make money, and those that did not would lose money. No 
longer would educational decisions be largely a function of 
political considerations. Instead, the focus would be on (1) 
meeting the educational demands of parents and students and (2) 
controlling costs. <p>
No educational plan is perfect, including the privatization 
option: we live in a world without panaceas. But some solutions 
are clearly better than others. <p>
After the relevant benefits and costs of current alternatives are 
weighed, the evidence continues to mount that an educational 
system involving private school options has the best chance of 
producing the outcomes we want at a minimum expenditure of 
resources. There are three specific types of evidence that lead 
us to believe such a system would give parents the kind of 
education they want at lower costs than would be the case for 
public schools. <p>
<center><h3>COMPETITION</center></h3><p> 
The first type of evidence comes from microeconomic theory 
concerning monopolies. In general, monopoly firms restrict 
output, raise prices above the marginal cost of production, 
underutilize plant capacity, waste resources, and often produce 
inferior quality products or services. Since public schools are a 
monopoly, one would expect public schools to function less 
efficiently than private schools. Replacing public schools with 
private schools would impose competitive restraints, forcing them 
to pay closer attention to client demands and the cost of 
satisfying those demands. Most public schools lack the incentives 
necessary to cause them to pay closer attention to their clients' 
wishes. <p>
<center><h3>EFFICIENCY</center></h3><p>
Empirical evidence represents a second type of support for the 
proposition that private schools operate more efficiently than 
public schools. Robert Genetski, for example, examined the costs 
of public and private schools in Chicago. His figures put the 
cost of private schools in that city at anywhere from 45 to 77 
percent of the cost of public schools. These figures resulted 
even after adjustments were made for the fact that public schools 
usually pay higher salaries than private schools, and must deal 
with students who have disabilities, language problems, financial 
deprivation, and social and intellectual disadvantages. <p>
According to a 1978 study of New York City schools, public 
schools spend $4,785 per pupil per year for non-handicapped 
students, while private schools spend $4,512. The difference in 
cost is even greater for handicapped students. The per student 
cost for handicapped students was $6,196 in public schools -- and 
$4,730 in private schools. One of the reasons for the cost 
differential with both handicapped and non-handicapped students 
is that public schools generally are more labor intensive than 
private schools, especially at the staff level. The New York 
study found this to be the case. <p>
<center><h3>COST </center></h3><p>
The third source of support for private options can be found in 
the success of privatization in other government functions. Many 
other traditional activities of government, from protective and 
custodial services to health care and transportation services, 
have already been privatized by some cities and counties. <p>
The evidence that privatized services are generally provided at 
lower cost than public services is overwhelming. In Privatizing 
the Public Sector, E.S. Savas provides many examples of 
successful privatization. Studies covering the United States, 
Canada, and Switzerland, for example, show that municipal solid 
waste collection is 61-71 percent more expensive when government 
provides it. Scottsdale, Arizona, found that a private firm could 
provide fire protection for 52 percent of the government agency's 
cost. In the Federal Republic of Germany, municipal bus service 
costs 160 percent more per kilometer than private service. <p>
In another study, nursing homes operated by the U.S. Veterans 
Administration had a per patient cost that was 83 percent higher 
than that for comparable private nursing homes. Reports on 
privatization efforts in Indianapolis, Indiana, and Newark, New 
Jersey, also point to improved service at lower cost. <p>
Often the debate over choice is muddled because of an inability 
to separate choice limited to pubic schools from public-private 
choice via vouchers, and either of these from a privatized 
system. For example, the empirical studies on choice published in 
a special issue of the Economics of Education Review are devoted 
to either public school choice or public-private choice via 
vouchers, but do not address a system consisting only of private 
school alternatives such as we describe. <p>
<center><h3>WHY SOME PEOPLE ARE CONCERNED</center></h3><p> 
Some of the controversy over the efficiency of private schools 
stems from the fact that while most private schools operate at 
lower cost than public schools, the kinds, amounts, and types of 
education they produce may not be comparable. While most private 
school supporters would be content to let the judgment about 
school product rest with parental choice in much the same way 
consumers judge supermarket standards, most critics of private 
school choice would be unwilling to accept such a proposition. 
Public school advocates have a strong philosophical bias against 
school variety and parents possessing the power to choose schools 
and programs of study. The steady march of school consolidation 
and standardization over the decades attests to this fact. <p>
Of course, there are valid concerns that do arise from, and often 
strong opposition that does surface to, options involving private 
schools. Even advocates see some problems to be overcome if 
schools are to introduce any meaningful choice system. <p>
<center><h3>THE BAD NEWS </center></h3><p>
The following list represents some of the concerns related to the 
implementation of a private school choice system. <p>
1. At least some students, teachers, and staff would find 
themselves temporarily or permanently dislocated as the new 
system was brought "on line" and new schools opened and/or 
ineffective schools restructured or closed. <p>
2. Schools in some areas could resegregate even though the net 
effect would probably be increased integration, especially for 
the inner city schools. <p>
3. Some parents might give only marginal thought to school 
choices, and they might need assistance in making their choices. <p>
4. Under any choice system, there would be the ever-present risk 
of state governments taking over more and more power through 
increased regulation.  <p>
5. The diversity of types of schools and curricula represents a 
potential danger. Some "fringe groups" would no doubt want to 
establish their own special schools. <p>
6. In the education market, as with markets in general, the 
public would need to be vigilant against fraud and deceit. <p>
7. Students in more populous areas would have far more options 
than students in rural areas. <p>
<center><h3>THE GOOD NEWS </center></h3><p>
Each of these concerns, along with others yet to be discovered, 
will deserve our attention. None of them, however, represents a 
"deal buster." The benefits of private school choice derive 
primarily from the increased flexibility and sensitivity of the 
system. Rather than a static bureaucratic monopoly, a system of 
choice would permit rapid and efficient change and growth. <p>
Even without the advantages of publicly provided funding, some 
private schools are forging ahead with newer and better ways of 
providing education. Jim Boyle formed Ombudsman Educational 
Services Ltd. and now operates 22 schools in Illinois, Minnesota, 
and Arizona, servicing a total of 800 students. The American 
Association of Educators in Private Practice, a new professional 
association of teachers in private enterprise schools, was formed 
recently by 50 teachers. Education Alternatives Inc. currently 
contracts with local authorities to operate specific public 
schools. This firm now has contracts to operate public schools in 
Florida, Maryland, Minnesota, and Arizona. <p>
Some private firms are already moving into position to take 
advantage of any opportunities that may arise from the school 
choice movement. The most widely publicized effort is that of 
Christopher Whittle, Chairman of Whittle Communications. This 
company has invested $60 million in The Edison Project, which 
plans to open 200 schools with 150,000 students by 1996 at a 
total investment of $2.45 billion. By the year 2010, this firm 
expects to have 2 million students coast to coast. Whittle has 
received financial commitments from a number of partners, and has 
put in place a team of advisors and specialists, i.e., 100 well-
known educators, businessmen, and other personalities. <p>
Several other major firms have also entered the for-profit 
education business. Sylvan Learning Centers, Huntington Learning 
Systems, and Britannica Learning Centers are franchised 
operations with schools operating across the nation. Even Burger 
King is operating quasi-private secondary schools in 14 cities 
under the name "Burger King Academies!" And IBM and Apple have 
recently expressed serious interest in starting profit-making 
schools, too. <p>
Definite signs are emerging that local, state, and federal 
governments are willing to encourage the movement toward public 
school privatization. The town of Epsom, New Hampshire, has 
instituted a $1,000 tax rebate for families sending their 
children to any school other than the local public school. 
Milwaukee, Wisconsin, has a voucher system already in place for 
1,000 ghetto children. For two years now, parents of these 
children have been allowed to select private schools and have the 
government pay $2,500 per student per year to the school 
selected. Colorado had a voucher proposal on the ballot in the 
1992 general election, but lost because of strong opposition from 
teachers' unions. California's proposal suffered a similar fate. <p>
<center><h3>WHY THE TIME IS NOW </center></h3><p>
Can the marketplace save our schools? <p>
In the United States, private school enrollment traditionally has 
been restricted by the fact that parents sending their children 
to private schools have had to pay private tuition AND public 
school taxes. Most parents have been unwilling or unable to 
shoulder such a financial burden. Statutory restrictions have 
also discouraged the formation of private schools. <p>
In recent years, however, a move appears to have gotten under way 
to remedy this situation through options involving choice. This 
trend should be openly encouraged. Real reform will come to the 
nation's schools only through free markets that permit private 
schools to compete for the students they educate. <p>
<i>James R Rinehart is the Phillip N. Truluck Professor of Public 
Policy/Economics and Director of the Center for Economics 
Education at Francis Marion University. Jackson F. Lee, Jr. is 
Professor of Education at Francis Marion University. </i><p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
