<title>Insider #34</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
The <a href="http://www.townhall.com">Heritage Foundation</a>
214 Massachusetts Ave., N.E.
Washington, D.C. 20002
Ph: (202) 546-4400
<hr>
<center>
<i>November 1993</i><p> 
<h2>Business/Education Insider #34</h2>
<b>Features:  <br>
Public Schools Failing, Says Education Department <br>
Newark Voucher Program <br>
Sweden Opts for Choice <br>
Proposition 174 Falls to Big Money <br>
Report Says Nation Still at Risk</b> <p>
</center>
<hr>
<br>
<center><h3>FOR-PROFIT PUBLIC SCHOOL MANAGEMENT SPREADS</h3></center><p> 
The Minneapolis School Board recently voted to hand over the 
management of all the city's public schools to Public Strategies 
Group, Inc., a private consulting firm that specializes in operating 
public organizations. The Minneapolis-based firm will manage the 
school district's 75 schools and $220 million budget. The school board 
would continue to set policy. The Minneapolis plan is the first 
district-wide privately run program in the country. Elsewhere, only a 
single school or small group of schools is run privately. <p>
Peter Hutchinson, President of Public Strategies, will replace 
the school superintendent if the state grants a waiver to allow a 
person without the traditional credentials to head the school system. 
Hutchinson's pay and the firm's fee will be tied to completion of 
goals such as gains in test scores, improved attendance, and declines 
in violent school incidents.<p>
Public Strategies hopes to revolutionize the way schools are run. 
The firm's CEO, Babak Armajani, says "We want to change the schools 
from the culture of bureaucracy to a culture that focuses on customer 
service, where the parents and students are the customers."<p>
Using management techniques from private schools, companies such 
as Public Strategies are confident they can provide better services 
than publicly run school districts for the same or even less money. 
Critics claim profits will take precedence over quality and 
efficiency. "There is a cynicism about the companies," says Albert 
Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teachers. "In every 
other sphere of life, if someone came along and said they have a 
special potion to fix schools, you wouldn't treat them as wonderful 
innovators. You would call them hucksters." <p>
But the experience to date suggests Shanker's view is unfounded. 
An earlier venture by Education Alternatives, Inc. (see BEI #8, 11, 
18, 19), a Minneapolis-based private, for-profit company, is in its 
third year of running the South Pointe Elementary School in Dade 
County, Florida, and has run nine public schools in Baltimore, 
Maryland, since August 1992. The company's plan is to test students to 
determine whether they learn best by doing, reading, or hearing, and 
then devise an individual learning plan for each student. Preliminary 
data from April-June 1993, indicate that the students in the Education 
Alternatives schools on average advanced at almost three times the 
rate of those in comparable classes in reading and math. <p>
These early results have satisfied many of the earlier critics 
about the motives of Education Alternatives, Inc. Elijah E. Cummings, 
a Maryland legislator whose district includes the neighborhood where 
the company has taken over the schools, states, "I was the company's 
No. 1 opponent because I had reservations about their profit motive. 
But it has changed the attitude not only of children but of teachers. 
Never have I seen this kind of turnaround."<p>
Parents and students also praise the new arrangement. Pamela 
Brown, a mother, told The New York Times recently, "A lot of parents 
say their kids come home singing. Kids are excited about going to 
school." Adds Sean Urquhart, a fifth grader, "It used to be a boring 
old school. Now its fun and exciting."<p>
Another company hoping to duplicate this Baltimore performance is 
the Edison Project (see BEI #18, 20, 24), headed by entrepreneur 
Christopher Whittle. Its original goal was to build two hundred for-
profit schools by 1996, at a cost of $2.5 billion. But this ambitious 
plan failed to draw sufficient investors, and the plan has now been 
scaled back to a joint public-private partnership, with public school 
systems providing 80 percent to 100 percent of the funds they 
currently spend on students, and private investors spending up to $3.5 
million to upgrade each school. Its new goal is to run six to ten 
charter schools by 1995.<p>
The Edison plan envisions a teacher-student ratio of one to 
sixteen, hiring and firing of teachers based on performance, school 
days of eight hours, school years of 210 days, a six-week summer 
break, a personal computer for each student that parents can also use 
to interact with school officials, stricter discipline, and a core 
curriculum.<p>
School districts intrigued with the idea of private management 
hope the ventures will provide better services at lower cost. Many 
will be looking carefully at Minneapolis to see if this proves to be 
the case. <p>
<i>For more information, contact Public Strategies Group, Inc., 275 
East 4th Street, Suite 710, St. Paul, MN 55101, (612) 227-9774; 
Education Alternatives, Inc., 1300 Norwest Financial Center, 7900 
Xerxes Avenue South, Minneapolis, MN 55431, (612) 832-0092; or the 
Edison Project, 1627 K Street, N.W., Suite 600, Washington, DC 20006, 
(202) 659-3556.</i><p>
<hr>
<br>
<h3><center>NATIONAL SCHOOL CHOICE IN SWEDEN</h3></center>
While America debates school choice, Sweden, the model of 
socialist experimentation, has opened up its entire school system to 
genuine competition.<p>
Before the advent of the school choice plan, which was introduced 
in 1992, Swedish government schools enjoyed a virtual monopoly in the 
education system: 99 percent of the Swedish school-age population 
attended public schools. Swedish officials concluded, however, that a 
monopolistic system does not work. "Monopoly is just as disastrous in 
schools as in any other area," says Under Secretary of Education Odd 
Eiken. "We need an alternative, competing system."<p>
Under the new national school choice plan, Swedish parents can 
choose any public or private school anywhere in Sweden. If a student 
chooses to attend a school other than a public school, he gets a 
voucher worth 85 percent of the average cost per student in his 
municipality. Swedish officials insist that a voucher worth 85 percent 
is better than one worth 100 percent, because it creates an incentive 
for parents to find more effective and less expensive schools.<p>
All private schools participating in the voucher program must be 
approved by the Ministry of Education. The basic requirements include 
a core curriculum, no racial or religious discrimination, and an 
agreement that the student's performance will be monitored and 
evaluated by the national evaluation system. Religious schools may 
participate in the voucher program.<p>
Since parliament approved the reform, the number of private 
schools has doubled in response to the demands of Swedish students and 
parents dissatisfied with the quality of government education. Says 
Eiken, "We get a new private school every week."A variety of 
organizations are starting these new schools. Christian and Montessori 
groups are taking the lead. But many have been formed by groups of 
low- and middle-income parents, who have formed companies or co-
operatives to operate schools in their own communities.<p>
Sweden plans to extend the school choice idea to its university 
system. Today, the Swedish government is deeply involved in university 
decision-making -- from faculty appointments to the type of research a 
university pursues. The Swedish government aims to replace this with 
an American-style system, in which universities will decide their own 
admission procedures as well as the way courses and study programs are 
organized. According to Per Unckel, the Swedish Minister of Science 
and Education, this is the only way to improve the system: "Higher 
education and research must be given extensive freedom, and the 
incentives to attain high standards."<p>
<i>For more information, write the Swedish Ministry of Education and 
Science, S-103, 33 Stockholm, SWEDEN.</i><p>
<hr>
<br>	
<h3><center>SLOW REFORM WORRIES BUSINESS LEADERS</h3></center><p>
A recent report by the Conference Board, a New York City-based 
business organization, says that business leaders are very concerned 
about the lack of progress in American schools. The report, entitled 
"Ten Years After A Nation At Risk," is based on a survey and 
interviews of business leaders and educators.<p>
Authored by Conference Board researchers Leonard Lund and 
Cathleen Wild, the report says that, "While affirming the good 
intentions and the effort in workplace programs," business leaders 
"are deeply disturbed by the lack of broad-based measurable results." 
According to the study, business leaders believe there must be a 
stronger commitment to systematic change, including deregulation and 
school choice. For example, retired IBM education director Jack 
Bowsher told the authors that, "The business leaders of this country 
must demand a total restructuring of the American public school system 
in future years. Then, the C.E.O.s and other well-intentioned leaders 
could decide if they wish to continue to support 'quick-fix feel-good' 
programs that only fine-tune the existing paradigm."<p>
Lund and Wild note that although huge amounts of money have been 
poured into the public school system by business over the past ten 
years since the Department of Education's A Nation At Risk report was 
released, there has been little measurable progress. As Bowsher puts 
it, "The return on investment in education is minimal when one applies 
real quality-control measurements to the public school system."<p>
<i>To obtain the report, call The Conference Board's customer-orders 
department at (800) 873-6273.</i><p>
<hr>
<br>
<h3><center>PRIVATE VOUCHER PROGRAMS FLOURISH </h3></center><p>
The Scholarship Fund for Inner-City Children, a private group 
based in Newark, New Jersey, is making school choice a reality for 
poor children who need it most. Founded in 1984, the Fund already has 
provided 13,700 scholarships.<p>
The fund will disburse $480,000 in scholarships during the 1993-
1994 school year to allow needy students to attend one of the 95 
Catholic inner-city elementary and secondary schools within the 
Archdiocese of Newark, which covers Essex, Hudson, Union, and Bergen 
counties. Only just over half of the scholarship students are 
Catholic. As Kevin Moriarty, the Fund's executive director, notes, 
"Most of our scholarship recipients live in areas where the public 
schools are ineffective and unsafe. For these children a Catholic 
school education represents a golden opportunity to escape from 
poverty and join the mainstream of society. The Fund together with 
Catholic schools gives thousands of children a choice of schools and a 
chance for a brighter future."<p>
In almost every case, a scholarship student graduates and goes on 
to college. "The graduation rate for Catholic high schools within the 
Archdiocese is more than 99 percent," says James H. Lynch, Jr., 
president of the Fund's Board of Trustees, "and 92 percent of their 
graduates enter college immediately upon graduation. If our 
organization can help children in need and at risk to attend schools 
that good, I know that we are doing something worthwhile." <p>
In addition to offering scholarships for elementary and secondary 
education, the Fund participates in programs with Fairleigh Dickinson 
University and Kean College, through which more than $250,000 in 
college scholarships have been awarded to Catholic high school 
graduates for the coming school year.<p>
The Scholarship Program also gives grants to schools to develop 
programs and curricula that address the particular needs of their 
students. For example, one recent grant was given to St. Patrick High 
School in Elizabeth to help establish a Special Education Program for 
students with learning disabilities. The Fund is providing $62,000 
this year to support twelve school-based educational programs similar 
to the one in Elizabeth.<p>
All of the money distributed by the Fund is the result of 
personal, foundation, and corporate donations. The DeWitt Wallace-
Reader's Digest Fund is the largest supporter of the Fund's 
scholarship program. The Samuel I. Newhouse Foundation and the Public 
Service Electric and Gas Company are the largest supporters of its 
school-based programs.<p>
Along with the Scholarship Fund, there are major programs in 
several other cities which help poor children attend the school of 
their choice. Among the private sponsors who perform this role are the 
Indiana-based Golden Rule Insurance Company (BEI #12, 17, 19), the 
Texas Public Policy Foundation (BEI #19), the Milwaukee-based Lynde 
and Harry Bradley Foundation (BEI #6, 21), the Georgia Public Policy 
Foundation (BEI #23), the Student/Sponsor Partnership in New York 
City, and the Washington, D.C.-based Charity for Choice (BEI #23). In 
addition, Bob Woodson, President of the National Center for 
Neighborhood Enterprise, is busy setting up a similar program in 
Newark. Low-income parents have been very eager to seize the 
opportunity to give their children a private alternative to failing 
inner-city schools.<p>
<i>For more information, write The Scholarship Fund for Inner-City 
Children at 31 Mulberry Street, Newark, New Jersey 07102, or call 
(201) 596-4313.</i><p>
<hr>
<br>
<h3><center>THE QUIET CRISIS:  SCHOOLS FAIL AMERICA'S BRIGHTEST</h3></center><p> 	
A recent report, "National Excellence: A Case for Developing 
America's Talent," published by the U.S. Department of Education, 
claims that America's public schools are failing their smartest 
students.  Many bright students, particularly poor and minority 
students, are not encouraged to work hard or master complex material, 
thereby learning less than their counterparts around the world. The 
result: an absence of high-achieving graduates, particularly in 
mathematics and science. <p>
According to the Department's report, "The U.S. shortage of 
graduate students in mathematics and science forces many large 
companies -- such as Texas Instruments, Bell Laboratories and IBM -- 
to fill jobs, particularly in research, with people educated outside 
the United States."<p>
Most gifted elementary school children have mastered from a third 
to half of the year's curriculum before the first day of class. But 
most teachers make little provision for the special needs of these 
children. In fact, the report finds that 84 percent of assignments for 
gifted students are the same as those for the rest of the class. In 
addition, a survey of gifted high school students finds that they 
spend less than an hour a day doing homework. As Secretary of 
Education Richard Riley writes in the foreword to the report, 
"Youngsters with gifts and talents that range from mathematical to 
musical are not challenged to work to their fullest potential."<p>
The official report urges public schools to let all children 
progress through challenging material at their own pace, and grouping 
students based on their interests and needs.<p>
<i>For a copy of the report, contact the Publications Department at 
the Department of Education, 400 Maryland Avenue, S.W., Washington, 
DC, 20202, (202) 401-3550.</i><p>
<hr>
<br>
<h3><center>BIG MONEY BEATS PROPOSITION 174 </h3></center><p>
While California's Proposition 174, which would have created a 
voucher system for California's schools, lost heavily on November 2, 
exit polls indicate that school choice in California is not dead. 
According to an election day exit poll by Luntz Weber Research and 
Strategic Services, more than half of those who voted against 
Proposition 174 would support a different school choice initiative, 
while only 18 percent of Californians are fully opposed to the concept 
of choice in education. The measure gained only 29 percent of the 
vote.<p>
Money appears to have been the biggest factor in Proposition 
174's defeat. School choice advocates were outspent by a 10-to-1 
margin; opponents raised over $16 million for an anti-voucher media 
blitz. Heading up the opposition campaign was the California Teacher's 
Association, who raised $12.5 million by assessing each of its members 
$57. The ad blitz began in mid-September, causing the Proposition to 
slip in the polls. With only $2.6 million available for its 
activities, the pro-voucher campaign could not fight the deluge of 
negative publicity.<p>
While anti-voucher forces had no trouble collecting money for 
their campaign, proponents of Proposition 174 had great difficulty. 
One reason for this is that business leaders were noticeably absent 
from the effort. Ken Kachigian, campaign manager for Proposition 174, 
summed up the situation: "The business community wimped out." Many in 
the business community do not realize the great amount of money the 
present education system is costing them. By not supporting true 
reforms like school choice, they have, in effect, played into the hand 
of the education establishment. Former Education Secretary William 
Bennett notes, "Business always likes to present itself as a friend of 
education, but ends up as a friend of the education establishment."<p>
Despite these difficulties and Proposition 174's defeat, a future 
choice initiative could pass. According to exit polls, 73 percent of 
voters would have voted for the choice measure if they had not felt 
that it would cut the per-pupil spending for public schools. In 
addition, nearly three-fourths of all California voters grade the 
California education system with a "C" or less. There also seems to be 
political capital in endorsing school choice, since 49 percent of the 
electorate say they would be more likely to vote for a public official 
who supports it. Finally, California voters rank the PTA as the single 
most credible organization in the education debate by a 2-to-1 ratio 
over the California Teacher's Association and a 5-to-1 ratio over the 
American Federation of Teachers.<p>
Although the statewide voucher plan was defeated, the threat of 
passage pushed the California state legis-lature into adopting several 
choice reforms to blunt the momentum. These included a mandate on 
school districts to permit choice within their districts, an expansion 
of inter-district choice, and a charter school measure. None of these 
would have been enacted, say choice proponents, without the threat of 
174.<p>
<hr>
<br>
<h3><center>SPEAKER'S CORNER </h3></center><p>
Do the teacher unions represent the ideas and interests of teachers?  
You decide:  <p>
A thousand public school teachers were asked, "If you had to pick one 
of the following as the area that should be given the highest priority 
in public education policy for the next few years, what would it be?" 
 Fully 80 percent of the teachers questioned replied that 
strengthening parents' roles in their children's education should 
receive priority.  <p>
The teacher unions, however, oppose letting parents choose the schools 
their children attend and other education reforms which increase 
parental involvement.  <p>
Seventy-three percent of teachers support expanding alternative 
certification to open the teaching field to qualified professionals 
with degrees in areas other than "education," such as scientists, 
historians, and writers.  <p>
The teacher unions oppose alternative teacher certification.  <p>
<i>Source:  Metropolitan Life Insurance Company Teachers Survey by Louis 
Harris and Associates, August 1993.</i> <p>
<a href="welcome.html.cgi">Introduction</a>
</body>
</html>
	 
 



 

 



