<html>
<head>
<title>SEX EDUCATION:  WHAT WORKS?</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<h2><center>SEX EDUCATION:	WHAT WORKS?</H2></center>
<hr size="3" width="30%">
<h3><a name="contents">Table of Contents</a></h3><br>
<a href="#abstinence">Why Abstinence Education?</a><br>
<a href="#choose">How to Choose a Good Abstinence Curriculum</a><br>
<a href="#focus">Focus of Curricula</a><br>
<a href="#methodology">Methodology of Curricula</a><br>
<a href="#references">References</a><br>
<a href="#options">Abstinence Program Options</a><br><br>
<hr>
<br>
The institutionalization of "family life" or sex education classes in public and private schools around the country has created a demand for curricula on the subject.  Unfortunately, the broad reach of organizations such as Planned Parenthood and SIECUS have left many school boards and parents thinking that there is no alternative except to teach "safe sex."  But there is an alternative that has shown to be even more effective than "safe sex" in reducing teen pregnancy and sexually-transmitted diseases -- Abstinence.  This paper is designed to help concerned school board members and parents choose a solid abstinence curriculum.<p>
<CENTER>
<h3><a name="abstinence">WHY ABSTINENCE EDUCATION?</a></h3><br></center>

Abstinence is the only strategy for preventing teenage pregnancy and sexually-transmitted diseases that is 100 percent effective.  According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, it is "the most effective solution" to unwanted pregnancy and sexual disease.<p>

Given the effectiveness of abstinence, a number of states--including Texas, California, Washington, Pennsylvania, Illinois, and Indiana-- have passed laws in recent years stipulating that public school sex education programs be abstinence-based. Many of these programs have produced promising results:
<p>
 <ul><li> 	San Marcos Junior High in San Marcos, California, adopted an abstinence-only curriculum developed by Teen-Aid, Inc., titled Sexuality, Commitment, and Family.  The year before the curriculum was implemented, 147 girls were reported pregnant.  But two years after the program's adoption, only 20 girls became pregnant.<br><br>
<li>Historically, the eighth-grade class at Nathan Hale Middle School in the Chicago suburb of Crestwood included a number of already pregnant girls.  When the school decided to adopt an abstinence program for the kids, many adults were skeptical.  But after three years of quality sessions with the abstinence program <i>Project Taking Charge</i>, the school graduated three pregnancy-free classes in a row.<br><br>
<li>In the Washington, D.C. chapter of "Best Friends," only one out of 400 girls has become pregnant since the program began.  Elayne Bennett, director of "Best Friends," says that between 20 and 70 pregnancies are common for the same sized group of fifth- to ninth-grade girls in the District of Columbia.  One "Best Friends" member explains, "I want to 												
	save my virginity for the man I marry....And I want my child to have a daddy."<br><br>
<li>An evaluation of the abstinence-based program Sex Respect:  <i>The Option of True Sexual Freedom</i> found that students participating in the program had considerably lower pregnancy rates than those in a comparison group.  Five percent of the female program participants and nine percent of the non-program students became pregnant in the two years following the program.<br><br>
<li>Emory University's abstinence-only curriculum, <i>Postponing Sexual Involvement</i>, teaches kids about abstinence through skill-building exercises on "how to say no."  An evaluation of the program showed that its participants were less likely to become sexually active than those not involved in the program.<br><br>
<li><i>AANCHOR</i>, an alternative national curriculum on responsibility, stresses the importance of family involvement and individual responsibility to prevent adolescent pregnancy.  An evaluation of the curriculum found three statistically significant differences between students receiving the AANCHOR curriculum and students receiving the standard school curriculum.  The students participating in AANCHOR were significantly more likely to report (1) higher family strengths, i.e., loyalty, emotional support, cohesion, (2) greater discussions with parents about sexual values and beliefs, and (3) more abstinent attitudes regarding premarital sexual involvement.<br><br>
<li>Students who participated in the abstinence-based <i>FACTS</i> curriculum showed significant pre-post effects occurring on the measures of (1) affirmation of abstinence, (2) rejection of permissiveness, and (3) future orientation and peer support for abstinence.  These attitudinal data are important indicators of delaying sexual activity.<br><br>
</ul>
<h3><center><a name="choose">HOW TO CHOOSE A GOOD ABSTINENCE CURRICULUM</a></h3></center>
In order to choose an appropriate abstinence curriculum, parents and school board members should study curricula for their focus, methodologies, and content.<p>

<h4><a name="focus">Focus of Curricula:</a></h4>  The growing interest in abstinence curriculum has caused many contraception programs to frame themselves as "abstinence-based," "abstinence-plus" or "comprehensive" because they mention abstinence as one of several options.  Such programs, however, communicate a mixed message to students which thereby tremendously weakens the abstinence message.  Some common characteristics of these "comprehensive" or "abstinence-plus" programs are that they (1) assume that teenagers are inevitably sexually active, (2) emphasize contraception and abortion, and (3) include affective decision-making (presenting abstinence one of many options from which to choose).  Thus, parents and school boards should choose a curriculum that avoids these danger points, and instead, upholds abstinence as the way to handle teen sex issues.<p>


<h4><a name="methodology">Methodology of Curricula:</a></h4>  The method used to deliver sex education material heavily influences the way students will respond to the abstinence message.  Effective abstinence programs are directive in their approach.  Dr. Onalee McGraw provides a comparative analysis of competing delivery models of sex education in her book <u>Foundations for Family Life Education</u>:<p>


<pre>
<u>DIRECTIVE</u>					<u>NON-DIRECTIVE</u>

Abstinence is defined as a positive	Abstinence is taught within the context
lifestylethat promotes self-control.	of contraceptive options.

Sexual rights and responsibilities	Sexual rights and responsibilities are
are not merely personal; they are	grounded in the right of the supposed
linked to society's needs and a 	"autonomous" individual to choose those
moral code.				actions that are right for him or her
					based on personally chosen values
					and classroom information.
					
Core values are taught as objectively  	Core values are taught as essentially true and good.				subjective.

Parental guidance is essential.		Only a minority of parents guide their
					children.

Teacher is role model and leader;	Teacher serves as facilitator to provide
provides clear principles and 		information and manage the group 
guidance.				process in the classroom.

All children need positive rationale    Children are becoming sexually active
for pre-marital abstinence and high 	earlier and nothing can be done to 
expectations from adults to form 	prevent this.
abstinent values.
<p></pre>
Directive abstinence education emphasizes the importance of values and attitudes, which is consistent with a U.S. Department of Education study, "The Role of Responsibility and Knowledge in Reducing Teenage Out-of-Wedlock Childbearing," which found that "adolescents with strong feelings of control over their lives, with higher educational expectations, and with parents who show concern and have higher educational expectations for their daughters have lower chances of experiencing teenage childbirth." <p>

Furthermore, students want help in saying "no" to sexual activity.  When Emory University surveyed 1,000 sexually active girls and asked them what they would most like to learn to reduce teen pregnancy, 84 percent responded, "How to say no without hurting the other person's feelings."   Moreover, a recent study done by Roper Starch in association with the Sexuality Information and Education Council of the United States (SIECUS) found that, of the teens who have had sex, 54 percent wish they would have waited until they were older to have sex. 

<p>
<h4><a name="content">Content of Curricula:</a></h4>  Sex education curricula vary greatlt by content , and parents should be particuarly concerned if the curriculum contains information or pictures too explicit for the intended audience. Caution is recommended even in cases in which  a particular sex education curriculum is widely used or endorsed by prominent organizations. For Example:
<br>
<ul>
<li>The two-million member National Education Association (NEA) endorses sex education programs that promote birth control and homosexuality.<br><br><p>
<li>The influential Sex Information and Education Council of the United States (SIECUS) has published a widely used set of goals for sex education curricula entitled, "<i>Guidelines for Comprehensive Sexuality Education:  Kindergarten - 12th Grade</i>.  The report promotes abortion, unmarried couples living together, and homosexual relationships as equal to heterosexual relationships.<br><br><p>
</ul>
<h4><a name="references">References:</a></h4>For more information on selecting a solid sex education curriculum, consider the following:<br><br><p>
<ul><li><i>Dinah Richard, Has Sex Education Failed Our Teenagers?:</i>  A Research Report.  Focus on the Family Publishing, 1990.<br><br>
