<head>
<title>EDUCATION, TECHNOLOGY 
	AND THE FAMILY</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<h2><center>	EDUCATION, TECHNOLOGY <br>
	AND THE FAMILY</h2>
	<h4><i>by<br>
	David M. Wagner</i></h4></center>
<hr size="3" width="30%"><br>

For someone who comes to you from a conservative organization, I have a somewhat radical speech to make.  I think that society is making more radical demands on education than most education professionals, and even education reformers, have yet admitted; and also that, paradoxically, these radical demands will actually add up to a good deal for the traditional family.<p>

One way to find out what demands society is making on education would be to listen to what leaders in the fields of business, education, and government are saying and then try to draw some general themes from their remarks.  You would hear, I think, a great deal about competitiveness, but also a great deal about something called diversity.  I suspect you would find that the back-to-basics movement of the early 1980s has faded, and that the world of the experts is presently divided between those who want schools to be vocational training centers for high-tech shop floors, and those who want them to be desensitization centers for initiating kids into what New York State Senator John Marchi calls "Manhattan attitudes."<p>

Actually, both those camps are missing the point, because both are working from assumptions based on educational centralism.  They think of education as a centralized function, in which a uniform product, determined by the education elite, is doled out to receptive and malleable pupils, as if on an assembly line.  I think society may be moving in a different direction than that.<p>

Commendably, there are some education reform proposals out there that are more radical.  Much of the rhetoric of these movements involves the need to, as they say, "break the mold."  One type of break-the-mold reform is exemplified by businessman Chris Whittle, and his project to create a network of low-cost, for-profit private schools.  This idea is mold-breaking, in the sense that it asks us to get past the long-held assumption that schools must be non-profit, and instead, to consider the possible role that the profit motive could play in securing good schools, just as it secures good consumer electronics.  On the other hand, while Mr. Whittle's idea breaks some molds, it <i>does </i>not break all.  It still conceives of education as a process that an elite does to a passive student body.  <p>

Another type of reform proposal is parental choice.  This movement originated with liberal sociologists in the '60s, and it was carried forward by conservatives 
in the 1980s.  The liberals who promoted it, such as Christopher Jencks, did so because it would promote equality.  Conservatives, on the other hand, liked it 
because it would empower families and disempower the state.  Opposition came, of course, from the organized interests who are dependent in one way or another on the existing public school quasi-monopoly.  Today, despite occasional setbacks, the choice movement appears to be gaining steam, with a coalition of supporters that is very diverse, both racially and ideologically.<p>

The parental choice movement is mold-breaking, because it questions the existing power structure in elementary and secondary education, and it deconstructs the authority-claims advanced by the education elites.  It also breaks molds by seeking to bring real accountability into public education for perhaps the first time since before Horace Mann.  Of all the organized education reform movements, the school choice movement is the most radical.  Yet even this movement declines to question the most deeply-held assumption of all -- that school is something you "go to" in order to "get ready," rather than something you do all your life.<p>

And yet, so radical are the changes taking place in our society, and most particularly in our technology, that some very basic assumptions may be coming into question: the assumption that school is something you "go to," entirely apart from both home life and professional life, and the assumption that the acquisition of education requires the services of an elite specially trained for that purpose.  <p>

A theory along these lines has recently been advanced by a physicist and former school teacher names Lewis J. Perelman.  Like the social critic George Gilder, Dr. Perelman belongs to the school of thought that sees computer technology as a force that will transform our lives and, on the way, weaken the behemoth state and empower individuals and families.  In terms of the conventional groupings within the wild, wonderful world of conservatism -- you've heard, perhaps, of neo-conservatives, or "neo-cons," and paleo-conservatives, or "paleo-cons"?  Well, perhaps we may call these people cyber-cons.<p>

Anyway, Dr. Perelman has written a book called <i>School's Out</i>.  The subtitle is:  <i>Hyperlearning</i>, <i>The New Technology</i>, and <i>The End of Education</i>.  His thesis is that technology is developing so fast that a number of concepts that we think we are familiar with will have to be re-thought.  The traditional paradigm of education, in which those who <i>know </i>impart knowledge to those who do <i>not yet know</i>, is becoming obsolete, because information is increasing so fast that, in effect, everyone is becoming a life-long learner.  But while information is becoming more voluminous, it is also becoming easier to store and retrieve.  More and more environments are becoming learning situations.  We are becoming a society of ongoing learners.<p>

The Perelman thesis goes on to suggest that schools, as institutions set apart from daily life in which young people spend a portion of their lives getting prepared for the adult world, are destined for the ash-heap of history.  Learning is no longer something that takes place apart from daily life; nor is it any longer something that can be said to be finished when the student reaches attains a high school diploma, or a college degree, or even a graduate/professional degree.<p>

Thus, Perelman ridicules all the present-day education reform movements as missing the point.   To illustrate, he draws an analogy between the new, computerized learning and the automobile:<p>

<blockquote>Imagine, for instance, that it's near the end of the nineteenth rather than the twentieth century.  A national task force on "excellence in horses" has issued a report exclaiming that America is "at risk" because its horse breeding and training are afflicted by a "rising tide of mediocrity."  Russian, Japanese, and German horses, the report warns, eat more oats, pull heavier loads, and can run faster and farther than American horses.  Since everyone knows that the horse is essential to agriculture, transportation, industry, and the military, it's obvious that an all-out effort is needed to raise the quality of U.S. horseflesh if America hopes to be competitive in the twentieth-century world.<br></blockquote>

<blockquote>Oh, by the way, the task force suggests, since the "horseless carriage" seems to be becoming pretty popular, all horses and their trainers should take a course in "automobile literacy" so they won't be scared by the noise of these curious contraptions.</blockquote>

I was particularly intrigued by Perelman's critique of the school choice movement.  He actually agrees with the school choice movement that parental choice is the indispensable threshold for education reform: without it, the continuing slide of our schools into mediocrity and ideology will be irreversible.<p>

But (Perelman's argument goes) if school choice is confined to choices <i>among schools</i>, as traditionally defined and maintained, then it is not choice enough.  This is for two reasons: one, school itself is becoming outmoded by new technology; two, good schools will not be able to start, expand, or multiply fast enough to accommodate demand.  Therefore, many families will not be able to take advantage of it, and this fact will fuel the anti-reform lobbying of those with a vested interest in the present quasi-monopoly.  Therefore, Perelman concludes:  "As long as `school' refers to the traditional structure of buildings and grounds with services delivered in boxes called classrooms to which customers must be transported by car or bus, `school choice' will be unable to meaningfully alter the quality or efficiency of education."<p>

What Perelman's analysis adds up to is that the principle of school choice must be followed to its logical conclusion, and that is, that the education of children, regardless of whether or not it is partly delegated to outsiders, must be seen first and foremost as a task for the home, and for the family.<p>


There is an extremely interesting fact that Perelman cites, and that was also cited in a recent ground-breaking Brookings Institution study favoring school choice, called <i>Politics, Markets, and America's Schools</i>, by John Chubb and Terry Moe.  Indeed, Perelman castigates Chubb and Moe for failing to realize the significance of this fact.  And that fact is this.  Chubb and Moe looked at various factors in the home lives of students, and correlated these with what they called "high performance schools" and "low performance schools," so as to see what features of home life have the biggest impact in making schools more effective.  By far and away, the home life factor that was most strongly correlated with effectiveness of the school was the <i>number of learning tools in the home</i>.  Students with more learning tools in the home -- such as computers, calculators, encyclopedias, and an abundance of books -- do better in school, leading to more apparent "effectiveness" on the part of that school.<p>

Lost in all the talk about "effective schools" was the truly significant finding here:  students learn more when the <i>homes </i>furnish intellectually stimulating environments.<p>

This leads to two conclusions: one would be that synergies between home and school can be very dynamic for students.  The other is that there may be a great future for one education reform movement that truly takes choice to its logical conclusion -- home-schooling.<p>

The home-schooling movement has grown phenomenally in the past thirty years.  It seems to have started in the 1960s with a few hippie parents who didn't want their children to be educated by "the Establishment."  Then it spread in the '70s to Christian families who didn't want their children educated by public schools that were perceived to be dominated by secular humanism.  In the '80s it spread to thousands of parents with graduate and professional degrees who just couldn't see the point of entrusting the education of their children to persons whom they saw as less qualified to teach than themselves.  Today, the movement is flourishing -- with hippies, Christians, intellectuals, and others, and some interesting overlaps between those groups.<p>

As for Perelman, he recommends many solutions in addition to home-schooling, but he also urges that parents look at home-schooling as an option.  And he urges that all families, whether they home-school or not, look on their family life as a part of their children's education.  In fact, after a great deal of prophecy about our high-tech future, Perelman ends his book with an exhortation to family togetherness.<p>

There is a portentous cultural convergence here: between high-tech cyber-radicals and traditional-values conservatives.  The link is this:  from the rise of nation-states during the Middle Ages, until recently, economic and industrial forces have been favorable to the growth of bureaucracy, which is a powerful rival to small-scale communities such as the family.  But the new technology, as Perelman argues at length, bypasses and cuts out bureaucracy.  Perhaps this is why defenders of bureaucratic interests are increasingly taking on an anti-technological tone, sometimes almost sounding like High Tories.  <p>


We've talked now at some length about elementary and secondary education.  What impact will the changes we are talking about have on higher education?  Very positive ones, quite possibly.  If education is going to change from a getting-ready process to a life-long endeavor, it would seem to follow that we will all find ourselves encouraged to maintain, throughout our lives, a certain student-like spirit.  Remember that the word "student" comes from the Latin verb "studere," which means to be fanatically interested in something.<p>

According to Perelman, one of the effects of the technology on education will be that academic degrees will decline in importance relative to actual knowledge.  Also, quite obviously, distances will matter less, as persons far apart will be able to communicate and share information in increasingly efficient and inexpensive ways.<p>

Therefore, I see a very interesting possibility: instead of our present-day universities, you will see new computer-linked communities of scholars spring up, linked by commonality of interest, and devoid of academic bureaucracy and infighting.  That may be the twenty-first century, but interestingly enough, if you take away the computer part, then it's also the thirteenth.  The great universities of Europe, in their infant days during the High Middle Ages, were basically just associations of scholars, who gathered together so as to learn from one another.  Young men who wanted to learn from those scholars would join them, and they were called "studentes," because they were extremely interested.  Perhaps the university of the twenty-first century will be like that, with future "studentes" tapping the scholars of their choice by computer.<p>

I've referred so heavily to Dr. Perelman that you must think I agree with him on everything.  Actually, there may be one point of divergence.  As I read him, I don't think he has a very high regard for the liberal arts as part of education.  My own view is that one can come to understand one's own society and culture only through close study of the best that has been thought and written in past societies and cultures -- that is, by participating in a trans-historical conversation on the great questions.  That is why I, personally, value the liberal arts (not, of course, that they are "liberal" in the modern sense -- in fact, many people consider them downright reactionary).<p>

In spite of this disagreement with Perelman, if it is one, I don't think I will be unhappy in the future that he describes, because I will have the option of sharing my interests in the liberal arts freely with others who truly share those interests.  The modern university is rapidly ceasing to be a place where such sharing is possible.  <p>

American higher education has followed a long, tortuous path.  During the nineteenth century, liberal arts education ceased to be considered intrinsically valuable and began to function instead as a means of maintaining a class structure.  People destined to be lawyers and bankers studied Greek philosophy and Roman poetry, not because they thought it would help them in banking or law, nor because they loved those things (were "studentes" of them) for their own sake, but because such studies served to distinguish them from those destined to be plumbers or auto mechanics.  If you doubt this, ask yourself what the young lady of yesteryear meant to communicate when she assured her parents that her beau was "a college man."  <p>

But that role for higher education has been upset by two major changes, one good, one bad:  the good change is that we are more egalitarian with regard to the professions.  The bad change is that a massive revolt against the liberal arts is being carried out, from within academia itself.<p>

To this problem, the cyber-future offers a possible solution: in the future, it simply won't matter if shrill and shallow ideologues take over what we now call the universities;  those who want the skills that the market demands will get them elsewhere.  And those who love the liberal arts for their own sake will be able to pursue them with others who share that love.<p>

So, to sum up, society today is demanding that education, at all levels, become less centralized, less bureaucratized, and less separated from home and family life.  These changes will be demanded by a knowledge-based economy; they will be facilitated by emerging technology; and they have the potential to restore hearth and home to their rightful place in the hierarchy of human values.<p><br>

     
<center>	***</center>
<fontsize=-1>

<i>David M. Wagner, Esq., is Director of Legal Policy at the Family Research Council.  This paper is the text of a speech given to the National Student Conference on National Affairs at Texas A&M University, on February 13, 1993.</fontsize=-1>
</i><p><br><br>
