<html>
<head>
<title>Toast by Dick Armey</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Toast by Congressman Dick Armey</h2>
<b>American Spectator Tribute to Ronals Reagan<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
May 17, 1995</b><br>
</center>
<hr>
<p>
Thank you, Ed Crane, for that kind introduction.  I was just thinking to myself ... if only this were a fund-raiser for the Reagan '96 campaign.<p>
But thank you all.  I'm honored to be here tonight to help you celebrate my hero, Ronald Reagan.  Thinking about Reagan's life, I'm reminded of what Yogi Berra said when informed that the City of Dublin had elected a Jewish mayor: "Only in America!"  Think of it.  Here was a former movie actor who brought down the most wicked regime the world has ever known, largely through the power of his words.  Only in America.<p>
They called him a far-right extremist -- said he was too conservative to be president.  And yet he won two landslides.  And when he left the Oval Office, he was one of the most truly beloved men ever to have held that high office.  Only in America.<p>
You know, that great lady, Clare Booth Luce, once offered the theory that American presidents are remembered by a single sentence.  Thus we say "Washington was the father of his country," "Lincoln saved the Union and freed the slaves," "FDR led the nation through depression and war."  And so naturally the question arises: How will Ronald Reagan be remembered?  Back while he was still president, Clare Booth Luce suggested: "He restored our pride and revived the economy."  Later, Margaret Thatcher would offer a pithier assessment: "He won the cold war without firing a shot."  Well, I hope it's not too presumptuous of me to add my own suggestion to the list.  I would simply say, "He liberated the world."  Yes, the world.  And not just from Soviet communism.  No, it goes deeper.  He liberated us from the peculiarly 20th-century notion that human progress depends on planners and experts.<p>
He had an abiding faith in ordinary people, because, unlike so many of this century's so-called wise men, he could see the inherent dignity of the human spirit.  Endlessly and eloquently, he reminded us that "democracy is the most deeply honorable form of government ever devised by man" and that the free market is the greatest engine of prosperity ever conceived.  He was the sort of person who really believed, as he said in his first Inaugural, that "you can see heroes every day going in and out of factory gates," and "you meet heroes across a counter -- and they're on both sides of that counter."
Because this humble, optimistic man of conviction was our president -- because this former actor dared to love freedom more than peace -- we stand tonight on the verge of an era of unimagined peace, prosperity, and personal liberty.  Only in America.<p>
Ladies and gentlemen, a toast.  To Ronald Reagan, the man who liberated the world.<p>
[ <a href="i-armey.html#speeches">Spotlight On The Speaker</a> ]
<p>
</body>
</html>
