</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head>
<title>Speech at The CLC</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Address by Congressman Dick Armey</h2>
<b>Conservative Leadership Conference<br>
Washington, D.C.<br>
December 3, 1994<br></b>
</center>
<hr><p>
Thank you for that kind welcome.  What a pleasure it is to be here tonight, and in the company of such good friends.  And seeing you all here reminds me of that old Gene Autry song.  We're "back in the saddle again."<p>
Morton is too humble to tell you this, but my staff and I first began planning our strategy for a Republican majority last year down at Briar Patch, his mountain cabin.  I don't know whether it was the woods or the fresh air or Morton's well-stocked larder, or what -- but all I can say is: "Keep throwin' us in that Briar Patch."<p>
I hope you'll pardon me for looking tired.  As you might imagine, Newt and I are getting a lot less sleep these days.  It's not easy taking over the Congress, streamlining the House, and planning for the first hundred days -- when you can't have even a moment to fish.<p>
Of course, as exciting and gratifying as our victory is, we need to remember -- and this is important -- we didn't win power, we gained responsibility.  We have a lot of hard work ahead of us.  And so tonight, I want to spend a few moments with the people who have worked so hard to make this majority come true, reflecting on the meaning of what's happened -- and what we need to do.<p>
In this first midterm election of the post-Cold War era, Americans made it dramatically clear what they want.  They want a return to normalcy.  They want a restoration of the good, solid old values that made this country great: limited government, economic opportunity, and personal responsibility.  And so we have a clear mandate.  We go into this exciting new era with a very clear idea of which values are going to guide our actions.<p>
We also have a clear agenda.  The American people expect us to fulfill our end of the Contract with America.  And we will.  In the first hundred days, we will bring to the floor of the House ten very specific pieces of legislation, debate them, and vote on them in a fair and open process.  And let me say, I take this obligation very seriously.  I am fully aware that the future of my political Party depends on our performance between January 3rd and Good Friday of 1995.<p>
I've found that, in politics, you can either be a bitter disappointment or a pleasant surprise.  Well, we intend to be a pleasant surprise.  We intend to produce a persistent, steady stream of good news coming out of Washington for the average American.<p>
Instead of raising taxes, we're going to cut taxes.  Instead of writing new regulations, we're going to repeal old ones.  Instead of producing more dependency, we're going to encourage self-reliance.  Whether the issue is poverty, crime, education, the environment, or even equality of incomes, we believe freedom offers a better solution than does government.  My hope is that, as our solutions are enacted, and the good news gets out, it's going to start sinking in.  People are going to find themselves looking at one another in amazement and delight and say, "Wow, what's going on up there?"<p>
I know, Paul Weyrich, you've expressed concerns that the Contract doesn't go far enough.  And if the Contract were the extent of our agenda, I'd say the same thing.  But the Contract is just the beginning.  I call it the shakedown cruise for the counter-revolution.<p>
After all, the welfare-dependency state took more than a hundred days to build.  And replacing it with a conservative opportunity society will also take more than a hundred days.  Doubtless there will be setbacks.  Sometimes we'll lose a few yards.  Sometimes we'll score.  Sometimes we'll have to throw long.  But with discipline and hard work, day in and day out, I'm confident we'll reach our goal and move beyond big government.<p>
You know, the liberals are already giving away their game plan.  They obviously take us for rubes.  They think we're going to come in like Attila the Hun and try to sack the place in a massive frontal assault -- and, they hope, get ourselves thrown out in '96.<p>
Well, in a former life, I was a marathon runner, and I learned the painful way that sprinters don't finish marathons.  A good steady pace wins the prize.  So I hate to break the bad news to my liberal colleagues, but we do not view ourselves as a temporary strike force -- we are a permanent presence.<p>
We will wage a patient, well-planned, well-coordinated campaign to replace the welfare-dependency state with a conservative opportunity society, not in one futile assault, but brick by brick and stone by stone.<p>
Our source of strength is this.  We trust people.  We respect the sense and know-how of the American citizen.  We trust people to spend their own money and make their own decisions.  We trust the typical American family more than we trust a bureaucracy to know what is best for that family.  Just look around.  Ordinary men and women are capable of extraordinary things, if only we let them.  After all, America itself offers the most eloquent proof that free people can do great things.
But just as we respect people's freedom, we also understand that freedom requires personal responsibility.  It is character that makes freedom work.  And the essence of character is a love for the truth.  Truth, honesty, integrity -- these things matter.  Unfortunately, one of the reasons Americans are so disappointed with their elected officials is that, for too long, Washington has been a city in which powerful people could not be trusted with either words or numbers.<p>
Take, for example, the eighties.  In the 1980s, we were a successful and generous people.  As our incomes rose, so did our giving -- a record decade for personal philanthropy.  For the revisionists to call it a "decade of greed" is not only untrue, it robs us of our most precious possession -- our understanding of our own experience.  It's hard to make good public policy in the nineties unless we understand the truth about the eighties.<p>
Another example: "compassion."  When conservatives look at the facts and conclude that government-created dependency may be hurting people and tearing apart families and communities, many of whom are poor African Americans living in miserable circumstances, we're often told we lack compassion.  Well, compassion without understanding can be the cruellest thing of all.<p>
Back when I was still a professor at the university, we had a janitor named Charlie.  And although he was slightly mentally retarded, Charlie was a good man who did his job faithfully, and to my knowledge without complaint.  Well, one day they raised the minimum wage, and Charlie lost his job.  Doubtless they thought they were being compassionate.  But it seems to me part of having compassion for people is seeing their potential.<p>
Our first tool, then, will be our honesty.  Our second tool will be discipline.  For years, we conservatives have tried to reduce the size of government by taking on one program at a time, only to suffer huge casualties in a kind of budgetary trench warfare.  What we need is a new strategy that enables us to outflank the special interests entirely.<p>
And that's why, by February 6, I hope to dedicate to President Reagan two very special birthday presents: the balanced-budget amendment and the line-item veto.  These powerful new tools -- together with a ban on unfunded mandates and a constitutional requirement for a super-majority to raise taxes -- will transform the fundamental question Congress asks itself from "whether to cut" to "what to cut."  Having to set priorities will do more to shrink big government than a hundred individual floor fights.<p>
And because the biggest source of spending pressures is the desire of incumbents to ensure their reelection, we will move swiftly to hold a first-ever vote on term limits.  The American people overwhelmingly support term limits for a very sound reason.  Term limits are the surest way to prevent lawmakers from building personal empires with other people's money.<p>
Now, there's been some confusion about this in the press, so let me just clarify.  With Newt Gingrich as our Speaker, we will schedule a vote on term limits.  And I will do all in my power to persuade two-thirds of our colleagues to vote "yes."<p>
One of the least publicized, but most exciting, parts of our Contract is our prescription for reining in what I call the "invisible foot" of government.  Federal regulations cost the American economy six hundred billion dollars a year -- more than we spend on national defense and social welfare combined.  Yet you won't find these costs counted anywhere in the budget.<p>  
Well, our Job Creation and Wage Enhancement Act includes three major reforms which strike fear into the heart of every radical environmentalist.  I'm speaking of the so-called "unholy trinity" of mandatory cost-benefit analysis, a regulatory budget, and compensation for "takings."  I don't want to make your eyes glaze over with the details, but the upshot will be a lot fewer harmful federal rules.
To give the economy a much-needed infusion of risk-taking, our job-creation bill cuts the capital gains tax in half and then ends the tax on illusory gains due only to inflation.  This policy is being called a sop to the rich.  But the truth is, any family that sells its home at a profit realizes a capital gain.  Most of the families that see a capital gain each year are firmly middle class.  Personally, I think we should leave capital gains untaxed altogether, as our international competitors do.  But this cut is an affordable down payment that will create jobs right away.<p>
And that's just the first of our proposed tax cuts.  Today, the typical American family pays 40 percent of its income in taxes -- more than it spends on food, shelter, and clothing combined.  To ease this burden, we want to let families keep a little more of their own money, with five hundred dollars per child taken off their yearly tax bill.  Incidentally, that five hundred dollars is the functional equivalent of a school choice voucher, because parents could use it to send their children to a non-government school.<p>
We'll also let folks save tax-free for that first home, a child's college tuition, or medical expenses.  And to further strengthen families, we want to provide generous tax relief to families who adopt a child or care for an elderly relative at home.<p>
But perhaps the most important thing we can do next year for America's families and for the future of our society is to address the growing crisis of out-of-wedlock births.  Today, three out of every ten births in America occur outside of marriage.  By the year 2000, four out of every ten births will be illegitimate, and among African Americans the rate will be a heart-breaking 75 percent.<p>
Our Personal Responsibility Act would try to end the perverse incentives we've created through our welfare system by channeling welfare and housing benefits away from unwed teenage mothers into block grants which the states would use to give assistance -- but not cash -- to young, fatherless children.<p>
What would this mean?  It would mean young people will tend to exercise more personal responsibility.  And those who find themselves in a difficult situation will be more likely to turn to the traditional "safety net" institutions -- family, friends, churches and private charities -- which will grow stronger when no longer displaced by government charity.  But the biggest beneficiaries will be the children themselves, who will be more likely to have the blessing of two loving parents in the home.<p>
And as I said before, the first hundred days is only the beginning.  We envision -- and we will work for -- a day when every family can send their children to the school of their choice.  We will work for a day when consumers can buy food without having to pay a special surcharge to the government.  And we will work for a day when any young person, of any color or creed, can grow up to fulfill his or her God-given potential in an America with the freest, the most open, and the most productive economy on earth.<p>
Well, I could go on all night, but I know Morton would have my hide.  So I'll just conclude with this thought.<p>
Some of you here can trace your roots to the Goldwater campaign.  And others came in with Ronald Reagan.  And still others of you have joined our ranks only recently.  Well, no matter when we came to the cause, we are all in this room tonight because we've devoted ourselves to a vision.<p>
We see Ronald Reagan's shining city on a hill as more than a fanciful image or a bygone way of life.  It is always before our mind's eye as the America we cherish and dream of, the America we want for our children, the America we strive to be.<p>
This election has given us the best opportunity in our lifetimes to build and strengthen that shining city.  If we do our jobs right over the next two years, if we show determination and discipline and courage and sacrifice, we will not only succeed, we will have redeemed all those years of patient labor spent working for this day.  With your support, with your patience, and with your prayers, I know our ideals will be "back in the saddle" for a good long time.<p>
Thank you.
<p>
[ <a href="i-armey.html#speeches">Spotlight On The Leader</a> ]
</body>
</html>
</DOC>
